<LP>
   SIR JAMES GOLDSMITH dropped his pursuit of B.A.T
Industries, thwarted by growing opposition to highly
leveraged hostile takeovers. The financier, whose initial
$21.13 billion bid for B.A.T was the second-largest in
history, faced obstacles in several U.S. states where the
British giant had operations. The final blow apparently was
California's recent decision to bar a change in control of
B.A.T's Farmers Insurance unit.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   General Motors expects to shut a Michigan assembly plant
in 1993, the latest in a series of closings due to slowing
sales. The UAW union has vowed to make job security a top
issue in coming contract talks with GM.
                                                                                                       

   The Supreme Court refused to hear an appeal by GM over a
warranty-related suit that may become a class action for
nearly 600,000 customers.
   ---
   AT&amp;T senior debt totaling $9.2 billion was upgraded by
Moody's, the first ratings boost since the 1984 breakup of
the Bell system.
   ---
   The IRS may be reluctant to loosen a tax regulation that
some investors say thwarts free trade in debt securities. The
decision, expected this week, involves reviving bearer bonds.
   ---
   Exxon's profit fell 29% in the first quarter due to
one-time items, while Amoco's net rose 1.7%. Higher oil
prices boosted exploration and production results at both
firms but hurt chemical and refining margins.
   ---
   Stock prices sank amid continued worries about higher
interest rates, while bond prices fell modestly. The Dow
Jones industrials closed off 29.28 points, at 2666.67. The
dollar rose.
                                                                                                       

   Oil prices continued to rebound on speculation that OPEC
may agree soon to curb its overproduction.
   ---
   Coca-Cola is moving into East Germany with a $140 million
investment. The soft-drink giant hopes to match its success
in West Germany.
   ---
   A key Gulf Power witness pleaded guilty to contempt and
tax charges. Ray Howell also agreed to cooperate with the
federal probe of political contributions by the Southern
unit.
   ---
   Three Asian nations were accused by the U.S. of exporting
more than $1 billion of synthetic-fiber sweaters to America
at unfairly low prices.
   ---
   Time Warner posted a $51 million loss for the first
quarter, reflecting the continued cost of its merger last
year. The company said earnings hit a record if those costs
are excluded.
   ---
   A proxy fight will be reviewed by the Supreme Court to
determine if shareholders may sue under federal law for
misleading proxy statements.
   ---
   A group of disabled people has joined forces with home
builders to oppose proposed guidelines to make apartment
buildings more accessible.
